<title type="html"><![CDATA[12/6 (Thu.) How to become fluent in English/The 20 most visited cities around the world in 2018 (Host: Jason)]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.royalclub.tw/bbs3/viewtopic.php?t=231&amp;p=245#p245"><![CDATA[
<span style="font-weight: bold">Session I: How to become fluent in English: 8 things you must do</span><br /><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A2OyNkT_UJA" class="postlink">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A2OyNkT_UJA</a><br /><br />Please watch the video to see the big picture about how to become fluent in English. The 8 things the speaker suggested in the video are as follows:<br />1.Get motivated<br />2.Read <br />3.Get a good language school or a good teacher <br />4.Write <br />5.Listen <br />6.Have conversations <br />7.Get a good dictionary <br />8.Have realistic goals<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Discussion Questions: </span><br />1.What’s your definition of fluency in English?<br />2.Do you agree that the most important thing to do is get motivated if you want to become fluent in English? Why or Why not?<br />3.Among the 8 things you must do to become fluent in English, what are your top 3 priorities you will focus on? Why?<br />4.Aside from the 8 things the speaker suggested, any other tips (such as TIE--Think In English) you would like to share?<br />5.Do you think there is a short cut to become fluent in English in a short period of time (for example, 3 months or 6 months)? Or do you agree with the speaker’s suggestion: Having realistic goals—doing a little reading, writing, listening and speaking every day. Eventually, you will speak English fluently.  <br /><br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Session II: The 20 most visited cities around the world in 2018</span><br /><a href="https://www.businessinsider.com/most-visited-cities-in-the-world-2018-9#1-bangkok-thailand-2198-million-international-visitors-20" class="postlink">https://www.businessinsider.com/most-visited-cities-in-the-world-2018-9#1-bangkok-thailand-2198-million-international-visitors-20</a><br />Tom Murray Nov. 7, 2018, 6:58 AM<br /><br />Mastercard has released its annual Global Destination Cities Index, which measures the rise and fall of travel to and within 162 cities around the world.<br /><br />The ranking measures visitor volume and spend to forecast the growth in visits to those cities in 2018.<br /><br />This year saw Bangkok retain the top spot from last year, which is unlikely to change due to a strong projected growth of 9.6% this year.<br /><br />Meanwhile, Dubai came out on top in terms of visitor spending — the average visitor spends $537 a day in the Middle Eastern city.<br /><br />Scroll down to see the 20 most visited cities in 2018, ranked in ascending order by the projected number of international visitors in 2018.<br /><br />20.Bali, Indonesia — 8.43 million international visitors.<br />19.Osaka, Japan — 8.78 million international visitors.<br />18.Barcelona, Spain — 9.06 million international visitors.<br />17.Hong Kong — 9.11 million international visitors.<br />16.Milan, Italy — 9.19 million international visitors.<br />15.Palma de Mallorca, Spain — 9.3 million international visitors.<br />14.Pattaya, Thailand — 9.56 million international visitors.<br />13.Makkah, Saudi Arabia — 9.73 million international visitors.<br />12.Phuket, Thailand — 10.08 million international visitors.<br />11.Seoul, South Korea — 10.13 million international visitors. <br />10.Antalya, Turkey — 11.27 million international visitors.<br />9.Tokyo, Japan — 12.12 million international visitors.<br />8.Istanbul, Turkey — 12.8 million international visitors.<br />7.Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia — 13.53 million international visitors.<br />6.New York City, USA — 13.67 million international visitors.<br />5.Singapore — 14.47 million international visitors.<br />4.Dubai, UAE — 16.66 million international visitors.<br />3.Paris, France — 17.95 million international visitors.<br />2.London, UK — 20.42 million international visitors.<br />1.Bangkok, Thailand — 21.98 million international visitors.<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Discussion Questions: </span><br />1.How many cities in the article have you heard or been to? Which one impressed you the most? Why?<br />2.Among the 20 most visited cities, Thailand gets 3 spots, especially with Bangkok retaining the top spot from last year. Why Thailand and Bangkok are so attractive to visitors?<br />3.Choose one city (not limiting the cities in the article) you want to share about. What drew you to that place? What was your impression before you went there? What was your impression after you came back?<br />4.When you are traveling abroad what would you focus on—scenic spots, food, cultures, histories, relaxation or other aspects? Please share with us.<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Agenda</span><br />7:00-7:25 Greetings and free talk<br />7:25-7:30 Opening remarks/ Newcomers self-introduction/ Grouping<br />(Session I)<br />7:30 ~ 8:10pm discussion session (40 mins)<br />8:10 ~ 8:25pm summarization (15 mins)<br />8:25 ~ 8:30pm Regrouping<br />(Session II)<br />8:30 ~9:10pm discussion session (40 mins)<br />9:10 ~9:25pm summarization (15 mins)<br />9:25 ~9:30pm Concluding remarks/feedback from newcomers<br /><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">The meeting place of Thursday:</span><br />丹堤咖啡寶慶店：台北市延平南路107號2F (上樓右邊第一區塊)<br />捷運資訊： 近台北捷運–西門站 (4號出口步行約2分鐘，康是美隔壁)<br />丹堤低消: NT$80元<br />最自由的全英文會話聚會,前三次不用交會費,加入會員終生會費NT$500，帶著開放與熱情來學英文<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.royalclub.tw/bbs3/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=827">Jason Tang</a> — Thu Nov 29, 2018 11:05 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
